<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>That's like making a zone private.... for your own selfish wants.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'll use your choice of words, but whose &quot;selfishness&quot; wins?  NB wants away from the overcrowding. . .so do guilds X, Y, Z, A, B, and C.  Once all 7 of those guilds are in Tactics or CoD or wherever, the overcrowding has just moved, it didn't diminish.  So whose &quot;selfishness&quot; wins, the selfishness of the guilds who earned their way up the chain, or the selfishness of those guilds who group up to take down flag mobs for &quot;more xp zones&quot;?  That's a zero sum question, and as long as the answer is &quot;hey, they got here on their own&quot;, then not much can be said.  I say this, because I am sure that when NB beat Behemoth, there were BOTS and Tindi members who said &quot;oh crap, there goes the zone&quot;, but at least they knew we beat it alone and not teamed with some other guild.<br>
<br>
Baysar,<br>
<br>
I don't buy that it's a double standard.  You are talking apples and oranges.  If someone asked me for help late at night with a Ragefire or Fear CR or some other helpful deed, and I'm not up to my neck in raid leadership issues, I'm very likely to help them (as is most of my guild), as I'm a helpful person by nature.  It doesn't make me a bad, unhelpful person because I see guilds teaming up to take flag mobs as against the spirit of the rotations and cheesy.  Like I said, apples and oranges.  The community is as great as its made out to be, we all respect each other's rotation mobs and (most of us) try and minimize our negative impact on other guilds.  That doesn't mean we all need to give away all our plat and powerlevel our fellow Rathians selflessly, in some skewed utopian view of what is good and right in the world.<br>
<br>
This caste thing you describe, although I don't agree that my goal or thoughts is for &quot;people to stay in their place&quot;, but for people to &quot;earn their way forward&quot;, I think is a social issue/phenomenon.  Take for example, your own guild in CoD.  How many of them could show up in CoD before you would get frustrated or worried that one of them would do something to negatively impact your game time (taking your named or even normal xp mobs, train you, etc).  Quite a lot probably, as most of us don't care *as much* when trained or killed by a friend.  Now start adding Tindi, NB, or LoM members. . .how many of us can show up before you get worried we might do something stupid to endanger your game time?  Now, add other guilds, who got into CoD because LoM or Tindi flagged their entire guild. . .  Where does your line of personal frustration cross from acceptable to &quot;well, time to go play the PS2&quot;?<br>
<br>
I agree, it sucks that PoP zones are many times the only really effective zones to xp in, and I think Verant should address this in revamped Cazic, and other revamped zones.  But I don't think abandoning the principles that the rotations are based on is the right answer just because they're flag mobs.  Sure, the letter of the rules isn't being violated, but the spirit sure is, as is the spirit of pride in accomplishment. <p>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.noble-blade.net&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.noble-blade.net/images/ezboard/sig-small.gif&quot; align=&quot;left&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Karadin Firethorne&lt;br&gt;Assassin of The Rathe&lt;br&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.noble-blade.net&quot;&gt;Noble Blade&lt;/a&gt; <br>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#222222><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=pocketsfullofgold@therathetravelagency>Pockets FullOfGold</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 27<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(2/14/03 4:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm50.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Teamwork</span><hr size=1> <br>
The Spirit of the accomplishment may be diminished, but the affect is still the same.  They get their flag to go to these next tiers.  Just like a guild/alliance who took out Trak, AoW, KT... their very first time, they've done it with assistance.  Sure that doesn't get them on the rotation because they didn't do it without help, but they still got the loot that dropped.  Even when my guildies/allies took out Trak for Barrd's Epic piece and we had help from some SoTE members, I felt very satisfied of what we accomplished.  While that does not give me a better feeling of accomplishment had we done it by ourselves, I still felt proud of the fact that we got something done I was not sure we could do in the first place.<br>
<br>
I guess it's all a matter of what you may believe to be of a satisfying nature.  While they get their Flags to go to the next tier zones and had help getting it done, it still satisfies them and gives some of their members a much better attitude (IMO).<br>
<br>
Hell, there may be people out there that get flagged to these zones that have no guild affiliation, or are one of the few guild members who get flagged.  Does this diminish what they accomplish because they didn't do it with their guild?  Would their guild have the ability to make the attempt?<br>
<br>
If someone who's not guild affiliated, or in a small guild such as mine that gets their Vex Thal key, should they not be allowed to enter just because they had to have help getting it?<br>
<br>
I have guild members who constantly ask for assistance trying to get flagged for 2nd Tier zones.  We may not have the numbers to help them so they get others to help.  Does this diminish the fact that they needed help from outside the guild to do it?  This is the same thing except at a much lower scale.<br>
<br>
If it accomplishes a means to an end for these people, then I congratulate them and hope they have fun in their further endeavours.  I do not believe it ruins the integrity of the rotation system that has been established and how its run.  This does not ruin established protocol for going onto a rotation.  It's cooperation between guilds, whether on a rotation or not, to complete a sequence that may not have been available for them to do otherwise.<br>
<br>
Pockets FullOfGold<br>
Level 59 Thief<br>
New OutRiders <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/btherathetravelagency.showUserPublicProfile?gid=baysarfk>BaysarFK</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 91<br> <font color=#00FFFF>(2/14/03 4:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm50.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=534.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Teamwork</span><hr size=1> Karadin Imma just curious why you are so concerned about the pride of accomplishment that other guilds are feeling when they have a raid with or without help from others?  IMO there is only one guild who you should care about pride of accomplishment - that is Noble Blade.<br>
<br>
